    "instruction": "Using metric.csv, for the full series compute global P95 for every (cmdb_id,kpi_name). Then, for cmdb_id in [\"cartservice-0\",\"cartservice-1\",\"cartservice-2\",\"adservice-0\",\"adservice-1\",\"adservice-2\",\"shippingservice-0\",\"shippingservice-1\",\"shippingservice-2\",\"currencyservice-0\"], find anomalies in 2022-03-21 01:30:00 to 2022-03-21 01:59:59 UTC+8 where metric.value > P95. Produce a compact summary per cmdb_id with columns: cmdb_id, num_faulty_kpis (count of component-KPIs with >=1 anomaly in window), earliest_anomaly_timestamp (UTC+8 across that component's KPIs), top_kpi (the kpi_name with largest breach_ratio), top_kpi_max_value, top_kpi_p95, top_kpi_breach_ratio. Return up to top 20 rows sorted by earliest_anomaly_timestamp ascending. Keep output bounded and compact."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have narrowed candidates and found two distinct anomaly clusters in the incident window (2022-03-21 01:30–01:59 UTC+8): (A) an early cluster starting at ~01:30 where many services (adservice-2, cartservice-*, shippingservice-*, etc.) show metric breaches (notably container.node-5.network_receive_MB spikes) and frontend pods emit 543 identical warning error_logs starting at 01:30:04; trace anomalies show short-lived latency spikes from frontend→cartservice around 01:31 and frontend→adservice around 01:34. (B) a later, strong node-level I/O/load anomaly on node-5 (system.io.svctm spike at 01:47 with breach_ratio ~3.08, load and io.wait earlier at ~01:40–01:47). According to the workflow and rules, we must now pinpoint, for each of the two failures, the exact root cause component and time by correlating the earliest per-component metric fault timestamps to trace and log evidence. The next atomic step is to get exact earliest anomaly timestamps per backend component (cartservice/adservice/shippingservice/currencyservice candidates) with the specific KPI that first breached and its value/p95/breach_ratio so we can identify which backend raised the first fault (around 01:30) and whether it precedes or follows the frontend error logs.",
